There's a leak in the department
and some of them end up dead.

467
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:34,378
- What?!
- Just sit tight.

468
00:37:34,586 --> 00:37:36,922
You don't seem to understand
what I'm saying.

469
00:37:37,089 --> 00:37:42,302
I am in a nightmare. This is my nightmare.
It's a nightmare, man. Get me out of here.

470
00:37:42,511 --> 00:37:46,515
I mean it. Don't call me.
It's not safe. I'll be in touch.

471
00:37:46,723 --> 00:37:49,268
Hello? Hello?

472
00:38:07,452 --> 00:38:08,870
Yeah?

473
00:38:18,130 --> 00:38:20,257
I brought you something.

474
00:38:20,424 --> 00:38:22,384
My brother gave it to me
when I was a little girl.

475
00:38:22,551 --> 00:38:24,344
I could never seem to get up on time.

476
00:38:24,511 --> 00:38:27,347
I set it for 5.

477
00:38:28,598 --> 00:38:32,686
<i>Out of bed, you daisy head.
Out of bed, you daisy head.</i>

478
00:38:32,853 --> 00:38:34,187
It always made me laugh.

479
00:38:34,354 --> 00:38:36,898
<i>Out of bed, you daisy head.</i>

480
00:38:37,899 --> 00:38:41,278
I thought being away
from your convent

481
00:38:41,445 --> 00:38:44,197
that even someone like you
could get lonely.

482
00:38:46,241 --> 00:38:47,951
Have a seat.

483
00:38:54,624 --> 00:38:58,253
- So which one are you?
- Mary Robert.

484
00:38:58,420 --> 00:39:01,214
You have a little trouble getting up
at 5:00 too, Mary Robert?

485
00:39:01,423 --> 00:39:05,886
Oh, not now. I get up a half an hour early
just to make sure.

486
00:39:06,053 --> 00:39:10,265
It's not just the mornings.
It's that, all my life,

487
00:39:10,682 --> 00:39:13,393
everybody seems to be doing
or catching on to things

488
00:39:13,560 --> 00:39:15,896
a second faster or better than me.

489
00:39:16,063 --> 00:39:19,524
Yeah, well, everybody's
playing catch-up nowadays.

490
00:39:19,691 --> 00:39:25,405
So, Mary Robert.
Did you always want to be a nun?

491
00:39:26,448 --> 00:39:31,161
I always knew that was my calling,
to lead a life of service, but, you see,

492
00:39:31,328 --> 00:39:36,625
I've always felt that there's something
inside me that I want to give.

493
00:39:36,792 --> 00:39:41,505
Something that's only me
and nobody else.

494
00:39:43,215 --> 00:39:47,636
Does that sound like a terrible thing?
Like pride?

495
00:39:49,304 --> 00:39:53,517
No, doesn't sound
like a terrible thing at all.

496
00:39:53,683 --> 00:39:57,020
I'm so happy that you've come
to join us, Mary Clarence.

497
00:40:04,444 --> 00:40:08,281
You know how sometimes it's as if
you have to be yourself or you'll just burst?

498
00:40:10,450 --> 00:40:12,327
Yep, I do.

499
00:40:14,246 --> 00:40:17,749
- Goodnight.
- Goodnight, Mary Robert.

500
00:40:26,883 --> 00:40:32,222
<i>Out of bed, you daisy head.
Out of bed, you daisy head.</i>

501
00:41:08,592 --> 00:41:12,137
- Hey, wait up.
- Hey.

502
00:41:38,288 --> 00:41:39,414
Nice tattoo.

503
00:41:46,463 --> 00:41:48,089
Hey, sister.

504
00:41:48,298 --> 00:41:51,009
<i>This jukebox got anything on it
from The Sound Of Music?</i>

505
00:42:09,027 --> 00:42:13,240
- Wanna dance, sister?
- Why? You don't have any rhythm.

506
00:42:19,120 --> 00:42:21,289
Young man,
take your foot down off that stool.

507
00:42:21,456 --> 00:42:22,916
Now have a seat. Have a seat.

508
00:42:27,170 --> 00:42:29,422
May I have a Coke, please?

509
00:42:45,105 --> 00:42:47,357
What are you doing in here?

510
00:42:53,780 --> 00:42:58,243
What are you guys doing here?
Look, you have to go. You have to go.

511
00:42:58,410 --> 00:43:02,789
Oh, never mind. Go, go.
Just go that way. Just go that way.

512
00:43:04,165 --> 00:43:08,295
Sister, expecting any more
of your friends?

513
00:43:09,337 --> 00:43:12,382
Now, you guys wanna tell me
what you're doing here?

514
00:43:12,549 --> 00:43:14,593
I thought that you might be
ministering to the winos,

515
00:43:14,759 --> 00:43:17,721
the way that you did in your convent
in Reno, and I thought I could help.

516
00:43:17,887 --> 00:43:20,515
And I saw her leave and it was very late,
so I followed.

517
00:43:20,682 --> 00:43:22,642
What are you doing here?

518
00:43:23,685 --> 00:43:27,897
I'm here to see a man
about a car for the convent.

519
00:43:28,064 --> 00:43:29,107
- Really?
<i>'</i> Did you get it?

520
00:43:29,274 --> 00:43:32,861
No, I didn't. And I'm gonna get you
out of here. Come on, come on, come on.

521
00:43:33,612 --> 00:43:35,614
Oh, a jukebox! Oh, one song.

522
00:43:35,780 --> 00:43:37,490
- Do you have a quarter?
- No, no, no.

523
00:43:37,657 --> 00:43:40,368
Come on, he does, all right.
It'll come back to you tenfold. Thanks.

524
00:43:40,535 --> 00:43:43,121
Hurry up. Hurry up.

525
00:43:45,915 --> 00:43:48,084
I love this song.

526
00:43:51,921 --> 00:43:54,215
One dance. I'll be right back.

527
00:44:37,842 --> 00:44:39,094
Come on, come on, come on.

528
00:44:39,260 --> 00:44:41,346
- No!
- Yes, yes, yes. Good night.

529
00:44:41,513 --> 00:44:44,849
- Come on. Let's go, go.
- I love this song.

530
00:44:45,016 --> 00:44:46,726
We had a lovely time. We'll be back.

531
00:44:46,893 --> 00:44:49,813
- Yes, we will. Good night.
- Thank you. Bless you.

532
00:44:51,439 --> 00:44:54,859
This turns into a nuns' bar,
I'm out of here.

533
00:44:56,945 --> 00:44:59,781
- I can't breathe.
- Just come on, come on.

534
00:44:59,948 --> 00:45:01,741
Stop the giggling. Let's go.

535
00:45:17,424 --> 00:45:22,178
The sisters have made clear to me
that they followed you of their own volition.

536
00:45:22,554 --> 00:45:25,432
But they would never have ventured out
at all at night

537
00:45:25,598 --> 00:45:27,600
had it not been for your example.

538
00:45:27,767 --> 00:45:30,770
Listen, they just don't want to be stuck
behind these walls all the time.

539
00:45:30,937 --> 00:45:33,857
These walls are the only
protection they have.

540
00:45:34,315 --> 00:45:39,154
The streets are no longer safe for them.
And they are certainly not safe for you.

541
00:45:39,320 --> 00:45:43,700
These robes no longer protect our sisters.
The walls do.

542
00:45:44,159 --> 00:45:46,077
I'm sorry.

543
00:45:47,537 --> 00:45:49,873
You really do care about them,
don't you?

544
00:45:50,498 --> 00:45:52,333
Yes, I do.

545
00:45:52,542 --> 00:45:55,462
And I care about you and your life.

546
00:45:56,880 --> 00:45:59,632
I shall ask Monsignor O'Hara
and Lieutenant Souther

547
00:45:59,799 --> 00:46:03,011
to find a safer and more suitable
situation for you.

548
00:46:03,219 --> 00:46:05,096
Oh, no, come on.
Don't send me away. Really.

549
00:46:05,305 --> 00:46:07,098
I'm just starting to get the hang of this.

550
00:46:07,515 --> 00:46:12,645
I mean, look, I'm not gonna endanger
anyone or anything else, I swear.

551
00:46:12,812 --> 00:46:15,815
What about forgiveness?
Isn't that what you preach?

552
00:46:16,024 --> 00:46:18,026
There's gotta be something around here
that I can do

553
00:46:18,193 --> 00:46:20,987
that's not gonna chip my nails
or annoy anybody.

554
00:46:21,154 --> 00:46:23,114
You're right, Mary Clarence.

555
00:46:23,281 --> 00:46:27,410
To err is human, to forgive divine.

556
00:46:27,577 --> 00:46:29,204
You may stay.

557
00:46:30,497 --> 00:46:34,209
But I shall restrict your activities
to a single task.

558
00:46:35,960 --> 00:46:37,921
What's that?

559
00:46:38,129 --> 00:46:41,216
Singing. You will join the choir.

560
00:46:43,426 --> 00:46:45,011
Choir? No.

561
00:46:45,220 --> 00:46:49,724
You will sleep and you will sing.
That will be your task until you leave.

562
00:46:49,974 --> 00:46:54,979
No. The choir?
I mean, have you heard them?

563
00:46:55,146 --> 00:46:58,233
The choir, Mary Clarence.

564
00:46:59,734 --> 00:47:01,277
Is this the choir rehearsal?

565
00:47:01,486 --> 00:47:04,656
Sure is. Come in and sing a spell.

566
00:47:06,241 --> 00:47:09,494
- Soprano or alto?
- Whatever.

567
00:47:09,661 --> 00:47:11,162
Thanks.

568
00:47:13,998 --> 00:47:16,918
- Hi there.
- Hello, sister.

569
00:47:26,261 --> 00:47:29,931
<i>Crown him with many crowns</i>

570
00:47:30,098 --> 00:47:33,226
<i>The lamb upon his throne</i>

571
00:47:33,393 --> 00:47:37,480
<i>All kingdoms of</i> the--

572
00:47:37,939 --> 00:47:39,983
Mary Clarence, are you with us?

573
00:47:40,400 --> 00:47:45,947
I don't know this one.
I'd better sit this one out. Excuse me.

574
00:47:46,865 --> 00:47:49,659
Reverend Mother says Mary Clarence
has a background in music.

575
00:47:49,826 --> 00:47:53,496
Really, Mary Clarence?
Were you a choir mistress?

576
00:47:53,663 --> 00:47:58,167
- Sort of freelance.
- Freelance? Really?

577
00:48:01,129 --> 00:48:06,509
You don't think I see? You think I took
vows yesterday? I know what you're up to.

578
00:48:06,759 --> 00:48:10,555
- You and Reverend Mother.
- What?

579
00:48:10,763 --> 00:48:15,393
You're a ringer. She brought you here
to replace me. Out with the old.

580
00:48:17,937 --> 00:48:19,814
Oh, could you help us, Mary Clarence?

581
00:48:19,981 --> 00:48:22,525
Mary Lazarus, you're terrific,
but we could really use some help.

582
00:48:22,692 --> 00:48:24,569
- Please, you've heard us.
- We're terrible.

583
00:48:25,153 --> 00:48:28,656
Please, would you do something for us,
please?

584
00:48:28,823 --> 00:48:34,287
Well, there's a word for this. Mutiny.

585
00:48:34,454 --> 00:48:37,373
So, Mary Clarence,
you think you can do better?

586
00:48:37,540 --> 00:48:40,418
I believe I'd like to see that.

587
00:48:40,585 --> 00:48:43,922
Go ahead, sister. Make them sing.

588
00:49:13,493 --> 00:49:14,786
Okay.

589
00:49:16,037 --> 00:49:17,622
Okay.

590
00:49:18,039 --> 00:49:20,083
Where are the basses?

591
00:49:20,875 --> 00:49:22,627
Oh, you should be over here.

592
00:49:23,419 --> 00:49:26,255
And the altos? Where are you?

593
00:49:26,422 --> 00:49:31,344
Sister, why don't you join them?
And, sopranos, where are you?

594
00:49:31,552 --> 00:49:34,347
Oh, you've got to come down this way.

595
00:49:36,474 --> 00:49:37,976
All right.

596
00:49:38,977 --> 00:49:42,814
Basses, I want you to give me a D.

597
00:49:42,981 --> 00:49:46,317
Altos, I want you to do a third above that.
Give me an F sharp.

598
00:49:46,484 --> 00:49:49,779
And sopranos, give me an A.

599
00:49:49,946 --> 00:49:52,573
Let me have Sister Alma
play it one time

600
00:49:52,740 --> 00:49:57,495
so we all know what we're going to do
and we'll go from there.

601
00:49:57,662 --> 00:50:00,498
Sister, will you give me
those notes, please?

602
00:50:06,129 --> 00:50:10,883
Okay? On three. One, two, three.

603
00:50:11,759 --> 00:50:14,303
Okay, okay, okay.

604
00:50:14,554 --> 00:50:16,389
Very, very nice.

605
00:50:16,556 --> 00:50:19,058
Sister, would you come
over here, please?

606
00:50:19,225 --> 00:50:23,187
Just slide right in here for me, please.
Right here.

607
00:50:23,354 --> 00:50:26,107
- That's a powerful instrument you have.
- Thank you.

608
00:50:26,357 --> 00:50:31,070
But I think it's probably a good idea
if we bring you down out of the rafters.

609
00:50:31,237 --> 00:50:33,406
I mean, everybody wants
to be close to God.

610
00:50:33,573 --> 00:50:35,950
I'm just not sure you can do it vocally.

611
00:50:36,492 --> 00:50:40,413
Okay? So I need you to sing an octave
below where you've been singing.

612
00:50:40,580 --> 00:50:41,748
Okey-dokey.

613
00:50:41,914 --> 00:50:45,418
And Sister Mary Robert,
could you come stand over here, please?

614
00:50:45,626 --> 00:50:47,086
Yeah, come on over.

615
00:50:47,253 --> 00:50:51,382
I noticed that you're moving your mouth,
but nothing's coming out.

616
00:50:51,549 --> 00:50:54,802
So I'd like to just hear you by yourself,
if you don't mind.

617
00:50:55,053 --> 00:50:58,014
Sister Alma,
could you give me an A, please?

618
00:51:01,350 --> 00:51:03,019
Alma.

619
00:51:03,895 --> 00:51:05,897
Check your battery.

620
00:51:07,523 --> 00:51:09,692
Give me an A, please.

621
00:51:13,571 --> 00:51:15,573
Okay. Wait.

622
00:51:16,532 --> 00:51:19,494
Try this. Close your eyes.

623
00:51:19,869 --> 00:51:22,997
Visualise yourself
in a room full of people.

624
00:51:23,247 --> 00:51:26,626
Lots of silverware, people dropping stuff,
talking loud, drunks.

625
00:51:26,793 --> 00:51:29,253
Women with trays going,
"What are you gonna have?"

626
00:51:29,962 --> 00:51:33,132
Your voice has to carry over the din.

627
00:51:33,341 --> 00:51:36,177
You have to get up over all of that
to be heard in the back of the room

628
00:51:36,344 --> 00:51:40,556
where I'm sitting, listening,
straining to hear you. Okay?

629
00:51:40,723 --> 00:51:44,560
Keep that in your mind when we do this.
Sister.

630
00:51:54,112 --> 00:51:57,031
We call that an A with an attitude.

631
00:51:57,240 --> 00:51:59,992
That's what you need.
You have to put attitude in what you sing.

632
00:52:00,159 --> 00:52:01,702
Have to think
about what you're singing.

633
00:52:01,869 --> 00:52:05,581
It's not just quacking. This is rejoicing.

634
00:52:05,748 --> 00:52:08,668
You are singing to the Lord.

635
00:52:08,876 --> 00:52:12,964
Let's review those notes again
and see if we can put it together. Sister.

636
00:52:15,550 --> 00:52:19,345
Basses. Altos, sopranos.

637
00:52:19,595 --> 00:52:22,431
On three. One, two, three.

638
00:52:28,229 --> 00:52:30,940
Oh, we did it.
We actually sang a chord.

639
00:52:31,107 --> 00:52:32,400
That was exciting.

640
00:52:32,567 --> 00:52:35,278
Yeah, you sang a chord
for two seconds.

641
00:52:35,444 --> 00:52:39,073
The next thing you have to learn how to do
is listen to each other.

642
00:52:39,240 --> 00:52:41,117
That's a big key. Big key.

643
00:52:41,284 --> 00:52:44,412
You must listen to each other
if you're going to be a group.

644
00:52:44,662 --> 00:52:45,955
I knew that.

645
00:52:47,331 --> 00:52:51,502
Mary Lazarus, as soon as I walked
in the door, I knew that you knew this.

646
00:52:51,669 --> 00:52:55,756
Now, you're somebody who's
into hard work and discipline, aren't you?

647
00:52:55,923 --> 00:53:00,678
- Of course, I'm a nun. Four popes now.
- Four?

648
00:53:02,013 --> 00:53:06,017
- How often do they rehearse?
- Twice a week, couple hours.

649
00:53:06,184 --> 00:53:09,604
Not enough. I mean, listen to them.
They really need a lot of work.

650
00:53:09,770 --> 00:53:11,731
They gotta rehearse every day.

651
00:53:11,898 --> 00:53:13,566
She's good.

652
00:53:13,733 --> 00:53:16,819
Well, do you think
they really could get better?

653
00:53:16,986 --> 00:53:20,781
- I don't know. They're pretty raw.
- Wet behind the ears.

654
00:53:20,990 --> 00:53:23,576
Oh, please, let us try.

655
00:53:25,161 --> 00:53:28,623
- This is gonna be hell.
- Tell me about it.

656
00:53:53,397 --> 00:53:58,402
Welcome this Sunday morning,
oh, ye few but faithful.

657
00:53:58,569 --> 00:54:02,782
The choir, I'm told, has elected
a new director, Sister Mary Clarence,

658
00:54:02,990 --> 00:54:06,410
who will lead them
in "Hail, Holy Queen."

659
00:55:57,938 --> 00:56:00,399
- What do you think's going on up there?
- I don't know, man.

660
00:56:53,160 --> 00:56:59,583
Hallelujah!

661
00:57:52,845 --> 00:57:57,600
Girl groups? Boogie-woogie on the piano?
What were you thinking?

662
00:57:57,808 --> 00:58:01,103
I was thinking more like Vegas.
You know, get some butts in the seats.

663
00:58:02,104 --> 00:58:07,651
And what next? Popcorn, curtain calls?
This is not a theatre or a casino.

664
00:58:07,860 --> 00:58:09,028
Yeah, but that's the problem.

665
00:58:09,195 --> 00:58:11,864
See, people like going to theatres
and they like going to casinos.

666
00:58:12,031 --> 00:58:15,075
But they don't like coming to church, why?
Because it's a drag.

667
00:58:15,242 --> 00:58:18,245
But we can change all that.
See, we could pack this joint.

668
00:58:18,454 --> 00:58:22,917
Through blasphemy?
You have corrupted the entire choir.

669
00:58:23,584 --> 00:58:25,503
Excuse me. Excuse me. Excuse me.

670
00:58:25,669 --> 00:58:30,466
How can you say that?
I worked my butt off with these women!

671
00:58:30,633 --> 00:58:33,469
They've given up their free time to do this
and they're good.

672
00:58:33,677 --> 00:58:36,847
I mean, sister, we could rock this place!

673
00:58:37,056 --> 00:58:38,098
Out of the question.

674
00:58:38,265 --> 00:58:41,602
As of tomorrow, Mary Lazarus
resumes her leadership of the choir.

675
00:58:41,769 --> 00:58:43,312
Come in!

676
00:58:44,563 --> 00:58:46,857
Reverend Mother,
I just wanted to congratulate you.

677
00:58:47,650 --> 00:58:51,820
I haven't enjoyed Mass this much in years.
What a marvellous programme.

678
00:58:52,029 --> 00:58:54,907
Innovative, inspiring.
You're to be commended.

679
00:58:55,115 --> 00:58:58,244
I can't wait till next Sunday
when the choir performs again.

680
00:58:58,494 --> 00:59:00,412
Did you see the people
walk in off the street?

681
00:59:00,621 --> 00:59:05,334
That music, that heavenly music.
Reverend Mother, it called to them.

682
00:59:06,293 --> 00:59:07,753
It did?

683
00:59:07,962 --> 00:59:09,255
I must tell the archbishop.

684
00:59:09,421 --> 00:59:12,091
I'll send him a personal letter
describing your efforts,

685
00:59:12,258 --> 00:59:15,094
your bold new fight
to keep your little convent alive.

686
00:59:15,261 --> 00:59:18,514
And you must also include this. This is
something she would never tell you herself,

687
00:59:18,681 --> 00:59:20,599
because this is the kind
of woman she is.

688
00:59:21,016 --> 00:59:25,229
Sisters, she wants us to go out into
the neighbourhood and meet the people.

689
00:59:28,107 --> 00:59:30,985
- Oh, this woman.
- Oh, bless her.

690
00:59:31,151 --> 00:59:33,779
There are so many problems out there
that we could maybe help with.

691
00:59:33,946 --> 00:59:36,073
I mean,
that's why many of us became nuns.

692
00:59:36,240 --> 00:59:38,284
Oh, it's really marvellous,
Reverend Mother.

693
00:59:38,450 --> 00:59:41,161
There's a lot we could do for them
besides pray, sister.

694
00:59:41,370 --> 00:59:42,871
You're a pioneer.

695
00:59:43,247 --> 00:59:48,544
Monsignor, surely you realise
how dangerous this neighbourhood is.

